Frisemark wrote:People who have military factbooks but then their military equipment is a bunch of stuff they just thought was cool…

…but in reality all of it uses different measurement standards, or avionics, or weaponry or parts yadda yadda.

I dunno. This is a tiny thing that’s more for my other hardware geeks here but I see it a lot

Eh, I try to keep things with some semblance of order, but it's also reliant on handwaving so I can screw around in II without too much care for my own hardware.

Honestly I'm not that much of a hardass for realism.

HOWEVER!

It does annoy me when suddenly people walk in saying they are MT, then whip out 5 gigacarriers, each one the size of a small country, every square inch covered in guns, and they expect me to somehow NOT notice it... And then, to further that, they lack escorts. Any attempts to throw a hypersonic weapon against it (be it a ballistic missile, hypersonic cruise missile or even a hypersonic glide vehicle) are (somehow) thwarted and putting a minor dent in it with anything is deemed godmodding.

Or this idea that somehow modern tech allows for superweapons a la Ace Combat, like the Arsenal Bird.

A reminder that in the Ace Combat universe, there was a massive jump in tech for a variety of reasons, hence, what is "modern" in that world would be "post modern" to NS, given such feats of engineering are not even remotely possible in an MT world.

Also this really, really dumb idea of "let's make everything bigger coz bigger is better". No, that's not how it works. Stop it. And stop making me cringe every time I have to scroll through a military factbook of an "MT" nation who has more Rattes than there are people in New York City, but the only thing making them "modern" is the fact that they are using composite armor on a comically grand scale.

Most people have little knowledge of atomic science, especially atomic weaponry. This is especially prevalent whenever people have a nuclear plant under construction near them. The ones on this website who are more...liberal in their nation's deployment of the weapons just think explosions cool and nuke make big boom.

They don't think about what would actually happen if, in a conventional peer-to-peer conflict, a developed country decided to deploy tactical nuclear weapons and presume a limited nuclear exchange.

Not to mention the disastrous environmental and geopolitical consequences of deploying nuclear weapons in a tactical capacity. Every nation in the modern age would immediately cut ties to you and whatever UN-equivalent your timeline has would absolutely go in on you, under the assumption your country is a threat to world peace and completely willing to use its nuclear armaments.
